<h3><strong>Project Description/Summary</strong></h3>
<p>Â This project is very similar to the <a href="https://jsbeginners.com/testimonials-project">Testimonials JavaScript Project.</a> I did find it a lot easier, however. For this image slider, when an arrow is clicked, the next image in the array shows up.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<h3><strong>New Things Learned or Refreshed</strong></h3>
<p>Before doing this project, I didn't realize how easy it was to make a slider project. I thought it was just a jQuery thing. Turns out I was wrong.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<h3><strong>Time to Code</strong></h3>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>This took about 15 minutes to code</p>
<h3><strong>Lines of Code</strong></h3>
<p>This took me 35 lines of code.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<h3><strong>Biggest Take Away(s)</strong></h3>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>Image sliders aren't a jQuery thing. All I had to do was access different images from inside of an array. And to make accessing each image easier, I just needed to make sure images had the same name but different numbers so they can be accessed by an index.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

